  <!-- OVERVIEW -->
  <h2>Overview</h2>
  <p>As Responsible Engineer for hardpoints on the T37 and T38 monocoque chassis, I was responsible for the full design-build-test cycle of all 25 structural attachment points that transfer suspension, harness, and safety loads into the composite sandwich panel chassis.</p>
  <p>The monocoque chassis cannot take highly localized shear and pullout loads on its own — hardpoints are the engineered solution that distributes these loads through the carbon fiber skins and honeycomb core without causing core failure, delamination, or loss of stiffness.</p>

  <!-- PROBLEM -->
  <h2>The Problem</h2>
  <p>The suspension hardpoints experience extreme cyclic loading — up to <strong>13,500 N in pullout and 5 kN in shear</strong> — and must maintain high stiffness to preserve camber compliance. The previous T36 design had a factor of safety of only <strong>1.05 against core shear buckling</strong> and bolts were failing in fatigue at an FoS of <strong>0.6</strong>.</p>

  <div class="highlight">
    <h4>Key Challenge</h4>
    <p>Core shear buckling reduces hardpoint stiffness by ~60%, which directly degrades camber compliance and costs up to 0.2 seconds per autocross lap. The design had to increase the yield FoS from 1.05 to 1.5 while minimizing mass impact on the endurance event (sensitivity: 0.62 s/kg).</p>
  </div>

  <!-- DESIGN SPACE -->
  <h2>Design Space Exploration</h2>
  <p>I evaluated five distinct hardpoint architectures before converging on the final design:</p>

  <table>
    <tr><th>Concept</th><th>Description</th><th>Pros</th><th>Cons</th></tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Carbon Core Taper</strong></td>
      <td>~30 ply carbon puck with 45° honeycomb core ramp</td>
      <td>Good stiffness and fatigue life, low delamination risk</td>
      <td>Core ramp manufacturing is difficult and error-prone</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Core Delete Puck</strong></td>
      <td>Remove core entirely, replace with solid carbon laminate</td>
      <td>High static strength, good for SES 1-time crash loads</td>
      <td>Very poor fatigue life under cyclic suspension loads</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Fully Potted</strong></td>
      <td>Fill entire void with structural adhesive (Loctite 9396)</td>
      <td>Excellent load distribution</td>
      <td>Extremely heavy — mass runaway</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Increased Foil Gauge</strong></td>
      <td>Thicker carbon skin locally at hardpoints (SpaceX Dragon approach)</td>
      <td>Best structural solution — aerospace standard</td>
      <td>Rejected at CDR due to insufficient validation data</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>CFRP Reinforcement + Potting Hybrid</strong></td>
      <td>Additional CFRP plies over hardpoint + increased potting radius + Epocast 1626</td>
      <td>Validated, achievable FoS targets, manageable mass</td>
      <td>More mass than foil gauge approach</td>
    </tr>
  </table>

