  <!-- SIMULATION -->
  <h2>Simulation & Validation</h2>
  <p>I built an ANSYS ACP model of the hardpoints and validated it against physical Instron test data. The model was used to evaluate design changes before committing to expensive test articles.</p>

  <h3>Model Validation</h3>
  <table>
    <tr><th>Core Thickness</th><th>Stiffness Error</th><th>Core Failure Load Error</th></tr>
    <tr><td>3/4"</td><td>-3.39%</td><td>7.17%</td></tr>
    <tr><td>1/2"</td><td>2.35%</td><td>13.33%</td></tr>
  </table>
  <p>The validated model allowed me to evaluate the lower bound of stiffness and shear buckling strength for new design variants before physical testing.</p>

  <h3>Simulation Results — Stiffness vs. Yield Force</h3>
  <div class="img-placeholder">[ Chart — Stiffness (N/mm) vs Force to Shear Core (kN), showing simulated and tested data points from 3/4" 0.001 to 1/2" 0.001 configurations, test points tracking within 3-13% of sim ]</div>

  <!-- SENSITIVITY -->
  <h2>Sensitivity Analysis</h2>
  <div class="img-row">
    <div class="img-placeholder">[ Chart — Stiffness vs. Lap Time: diminishing returns above 1000 N/mm, target >4000 N/mm at 0.143s delta ]</div>
    <div class="img-placeholder">[ Chart — Mass vs. Lap Time: Autocross 0.028 s/kg (flat), Endurance 0.619 s/kg (steep) ]</div>
  </div>
  <p><strong>Stiffness:</strong> Diminishing returns on lap time improvement begin at ~1,000 N/mm. Our target of >4,000 N/mm captures 0.143 seconds of autocross improvement while staying well above the diminishing returns threshold.</p>
  <p><strong>Mass:</strong> The endurance event is 22x more mass-sensitive than autocross (0.62 vs 0.028 s/kg). This drove the decision to use Epocast 1626 (365g per hardpoint) over Loctite 9396 (640g) — a 43% mass reduction in potting compound.</p>

  <!-- FINAL DESIGN -->
  <h2>Final Design</h2>
  <p>The final design incorporated four key changes to the Lower A-arm hardpoints:</p>

  <div class="stat-row">
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="num">1" → 2"</div>
      <div class="label">Potting Radius Increase</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="num">+3</div>
      <div class="label">CFRP Plies Added</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="num">M4 → M5</div>
      <div class="label">Bolt Upsize</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="num">9396 → 1626</div>
      <div class="label">Potting Compound Change</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>Potting Radius Trade Study</h3>
  <table>
    <tr><th>Potting Radius</th><th>Theoretical Shear Buckling Force</th><th>Yield FoS</th><th>Mass (9396)</th><th>Mass (Epocast 1626)</th></tr>
    <tr><td>1" (baseline)</td><td>15 kN (tested)</td><td>1.11</td><td>640 g</td><td>365 g</td></tr>
    <tr><td>1.5"</td><td>18 kN</td><td>1.33</td><td>1,028 g</td><td>586 g</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>2" (selected)</strong></td><td><strong>21 kN</strong></td><td><strong>1.56</strong></td><td>1,460 g</td><td><strong>832 g</strong></td></tr>
  </table>
  <p>The 2" potting radius with Epocast 1626 met the 1.5 FoS target while keeping mass 43% lower than the equivalent Loctite 9396 configuration.</p>

  <h3>Bolt Fatigue Fix</h3>
  <p>M4 bolts were failing in fatigue at an FoS of 0.6 — well below the 1.75 target. Upsizing to M5 increased preload from 7 kN to 12 kN, theoretically eliminating the bolt tensile fatigue failure mode entirely.</p>

