  <!-- HARDPOINT TYPES -->
  <h2>Hardpoint Configurations</h2>

  <h3>SES Hardpoints (Crash Loads)</h3>
  <p>Roll hoop, lap belt, anti-sub, and shoulder harness hardpoints are governed by the SES rules. These use core-delete carbon pucks (~30 plies) designed to survive a 1-time 45g crash load. The roll hoop hardpoint uses a fully potted configuration due to geometric constraints.</p>

  <h3>Suspension Hardpoints (Cyclic Loads)</h3>
  <p>25 hardpoints transferring suspension loads into the chassis. These use carbon pucks with 45° core tapers and the new CFRP reinforcement + Epocast 1626 potting for the highly loaded lower A-arm positions.</p>

  <h3>Historical Comparison</h3>
  <table>
    <tr><th></th><th>T34</th><th>T35 (repaired)</th><th>T36 / T37</th></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Stiffness (N/mm)</strong></td><td>1,238</td><td>1,548</td><td>5,000+</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Yield (N)</strong></td><td>10,000</td><td>20,000</td><td>14,000 → 21,000</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Mass per HP (g)</strong></td><td>200</td><td>1,000</td><td>50 – 200</td></tr>
  </table>

  <!-- REFLECTION -->
  <h2>Reflection & Lessons Learned</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Start dev testing early:</strong> October at the latest. Final designs must be locked by early December.</li>
    <li><strong>Validate before CDR:</strong> The increased foil gauge design (aerospace best practice, used on SpaceX Dragon) was rejected at CDR because I didn't have Instron data to back it up. Future teams should pursue this with early testing.</li>
    <li><strong>Core ramp QA is critical:</strong> Bad core ramps (cells standing upright instead of properly collapsed) are a hidden failure mode. 3D-printed check fixtures were essential.</li>
    <li><strong>Sim-to-test correlation:</strong> The ANSYS ACP model tracked within 3–13% of physical tests — good enough for preliminary design decisions, but always validate with hardware.</li>
    <li><strong>Potting compound matters:</strong> Switching from Loctite 9396 to Epocast 1626 saved 43% mass with equivalent structural performance.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="highlight">
    <h4>Future Recommendation</h4>
    <p>The best path forward for UWFM hardpoints is the increased foil gauge approach — locally thicker carbon skin at hardpoint locations, similar to what SpaceX uses on Dragon. This eliminates the need for potting entirely. It just needs early-season Instron validation data to pass CDR.</p>
